Notice that $(i)(i^2) = i(-1) = -i = i^3$. Since exponentiation is distributive, we see that $i^{600} + i^{599} + \cdots + i^3$ and $i^{600} + i^{599} + \cdots + i^3 + i^2$ must be equal. Hence, our answer is equal to the sum of a finite geometric sequence with the common ratio $i$ and first term $i = i^1$. The sum of a finite geometric series is equal to
\begin{align*}
\frac{i^2 - i^{601}}{1-i} &= \frac{(-1) - (i)(-1)}{(1)(-1)-i} \\
&= \frac{-1 + i}{1+i} \\
&= \frac{i-1}{i+1} \cdot \frac{i}{i} = \boxed{-\frac{1+i}{2}}.
\end{align*}
